      <entry corresp="muṟam[DEDR5005]">
        <form xml:lang="ta">muṟam</form>
        <gramGrp><gram>noun</gram></gramGrp>
        <sense><def xml:lang="en">[type of?] winnowing fan</def>
<usg xml:lang="en">
</usg>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Narrinai/NA376.xml?id=NA376&amp;w=0,2">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>muṟam</w> <w>cevi</w> <w>yāṉai<c type="geminated">t</c></w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">elephant with ears [like] winnowing fans</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Narrinai/NA376.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DNA376%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(1)"><expan ref="#NA"/> 376, line 1</ref>
</cit>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kalittokai/Kali052.xml?id=Kali52&amp;w=0,7">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>muṟam</w> <w>cevi</w> <w>maṟai<c type="geminated">p</c></w> <w>pāypu</w> <w>muraṇ</w> <w>ceyta</w> <w>puli</w> <w>ceṟṟu</w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">[the elephant] killing the tiger that has committed hostility by stealthily leaping for [its] ears</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kalittokai/Kali052.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DKali52%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(1)"><expan ref="#Kali"/> 52, line 1</ref>
</cit>
<cit>
            <ref target="https://www.ifpindia.org/digitaldb/site/digital_tevaram/U_TEV/DM1_131.HTM#p7"><expan ref="#Tev"/> 1.131.7.3f.</ref>
  <q xml:lang="ta">eḻil kuṟavar ciṟumimārkaḷ | muṟaṅkaḷiṉāl koḻittu maṇi cela</q> 
  <q xml:lang="en">as the gems come out when the graceful little girls of the hill people sift with winnowing fans</q>
  </cit>
<note xml:lang="en">
All six early occurrences, including those from the two oldest <foreign xml:lang="ta">Peruṅkāppiyam</foreign>-s, form part of a miniature formulaic system that describe the ears of an elephant – the quoted <expan ref="#Kali"/> passage breaks up the formula and relegates the missing <foreign xml:lang="ta">yāṉai</foreign> to the end of line 4. It is only the <expan ref="#Tev"/> passage that allows a more direct understanding of what the object is used for. Of course modern dictionaries distinguish <foreign xml:lang="ta">cuḷaku</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">muṟam</foreign> both by form and by size, but from the available quotations one may wonder whether <foreign xml:lang="ta">cuḷaku</foreign> was used as a piece of kitchen equipment in food production while <foreign xml:lang="ta">muṟam</foreign> served other extended household purposes.
</note>
<note xml:lang="en">
Just like <foreign xml:lang="ta">cuḷaku</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="ta">muṟam</foreign> is not glossed by any early commentator, thus making it clear that this too was regarded as an ordinary word not in need of explanation. 
</note></sense>
